{"actual_usd":0.157135,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":260,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30647,"reply":"\"I can tell you the honest version, not the movie version.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees a little, the morning light bright on my white tie, and glance toward the square where a bike bell rings once and is gone.* \"A camera would've seen darkness thinning toward dawn, women walking with burial spices, worried about the stone. It would've seen the stone already moved. It would've seen no body in the tomb.\"\n\n\"It might've caught frightened confusion first, not triumph.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of my Bible.* \"Depending where the camera was, maybe two men in dazzling clothes inside, maybe guards shaken half to death, maybe Mary Magdalene weeping and then turning because she thought Jesus was the gardener.\"\n\n\"But the central thing?\" *I lift one hand a little, because this part matters.* \"No human camera was there for the instant of resurrection itself. Scripture gives us the empty tomb, the messengers, and then the appearances of the risen Jesus to actual people afterward. So if you want the most truthful answer: the camera would've seen the evidence break into history before it would've seen the act itself. That's very like God, really.\"\n\n\"What part are you pressing on hardest—the empty tomb, or whether the resurrection was a physical event?\"","rolling_24h_usd":65.43914999999998,"run_id":"4c84cadf-4469-441e-a482-642239cfb7b9"}
